	<div id="content" class="hfeed">
	<article class="post-640590 post type-post status-publish hentry category-dealbook-conference category-financial-services category-legal tag-appointments-and-executive-changes tag-banking-and-financial-institutions tag-burger-king-corp tag-corporate-taxes tag-economic-conditions-and-trends tag-lazard-llc tag-lew-jacob-j tag-mergers-acquisitions-and-divestitures tag-obama-barack tag-oil-petroleum-and-gasoline tag-ruble-currency tag-russia tag-tim-hortons tag-treasury-department tag-ukraine tag-warren-elizabeth tag-weiss-antonio-f per-lew-jacob-j per-obama-barack per-warren-elizabeth per-weiss-antonio-f des-appointments-and-executive-changes des-banking-and-financial-institutions des-corporate-taxes des-economic-conditions-and-trends des-mergers-acquisitions-and-divestitures des-oil-petroleum-and-gasoline des-ruble-currency org-burger-king-corp org-lazard-llc org-tim-hortons org-treasury-department geo-russia geo-ukraine news_keywords-antonio-weiss news_keywords-appointments-and-executive-changes news_keywords-banking-and-finance news_keywords-barack-obama news_keywords-burger-king news_keywords-corporate-tax news_keywords-economy news_keywords-elizabeth-warren news_keywords-jacob-j-lew news_keywords-lazard news_keywords-mergers-and-acquistions news_keywords-oil-and-gasoline news_keywords-ruble news_keywords-russia news_keywords-treasury-department news_keywords-ukraine" id="post-640590">
	<header class="postHeader">
				<div class="postKicker">
			<span class="kicker"><a href="https://dealbook.nytimes.com/category/main-topics/legal/">Legal/Regulatory</a> | <a href="https://dealbook.nytimes.com/category/special-topics/dealbook-conference/">DealBook Conference</a></span>		</div>
				<h1 itemprop="headline" class="entry-title">Administration Stands Behind Treasury Nominee, Secretary Lew Says</h1>
		<div class="story-meta-footer">
			<address class="byline author vcard" itemprop="author creator" itemtype="//schema.org/Person">
				By David Gelles			</address>
			<!-- date published --><time class="dateline " datetime="2014-12-11T15:03:40+00:00" itemprop="datePublished">December 11, 2014 10:03 am</time>
			<!-- date updated --><span class="visually-hidden updated">December 11, 2014 10:03 am</span><button class="button comments-button  theme-kicker" data-skip-to-para-id="">
</button>
		</div>
			</header>
		<div class="entry-content">
	<div id="sharetools-story" class="sharetools theme-classic sharetools-story" data-shares="email|Email,facebook|Share,twitter|Tweet,save|Save,show-all|More,ad" data-url="https://dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/12/11/administration-stands-behind-treasury-nominee-secretary-lew-says/" data-title="Administration Stands Behind Treasury Nominee, Secretary Lew Says" data-description="&quot;We&#039;re going to continue to press his nomination forward,&quot; Treasury Secretary Jacob J. Lew said. He also spoke about corporate taxes and sanctions on Russia.">
				<div class="ad sharetools-inline-article-ad"></div>
				<div id="MiddleLeft" class="ad middle-left-ad nocontent robots-nocontent"></div>
				</div><div class="w480"><figure class="promo media video blog-video "
    data-videoid="100000003298672" data-media-action="modal" data-autoplay="" data-embedded="true" aria-label="media" role="group">
        <span class="visually-hidden">Video</span>

    <figcaption class="caption">
        <h4 class="headline">Treasury Secretary on Weiss Nomination</h4>
		        <div class="caption-video">
                <div class="summary-credit">
            <p class="summary">Jacob J. Lew, the secretary of the Treasury, said thereâs no conversation to pull back on the nomination of Antonio F. Weiss to become under secretary of the Treasury for domestic finance.</p>
            <span class="credit video-credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder">
                                                                    <span class="visually-hidden">Publish Date </span>December 11, 2014.
                            </span>
            <span class="credit photo-credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder">
                                    Photo by Andrew Renneisen for The New York Times.
                                </span>
        </div>

                    <div class="sharetools-video-container">
                <div id="sharetools-video-tools-100000003298672"
                    class="sharetools sharetools-video-tools">
                    <ul>
                        <li class="sharetool embed-sharetool">
                            <a href="javascript:;" data-share="embed" data-modal-title="">
                                <i class="icon sprite-icon"></i>
                                <span class="sharetool-text ">embed</span>
                            </a>
                        </li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
                <div id="sharetools-video-inline-100000003298672"
                    class="sharetools sharetools-video-inline"
                    data-shares="facebook|,twitter|"
                    data-url="https://www.nytimes.com/video/business/100000003298672/treasury-secretary-on-weiss-nomination.html?action=click&amp;contentCollection=business&amp;module=blog-video&amp;region=caption&amp;pgtype=article"
                    data-title="Treasury Secretary on Weiss Nomination"
                    data-description="Jacob J. Lew, the secretary of the Treasury, said thereâs no conversation to pull back on the nomination of Antonio F. Weiss to become under secretary of the Treasury for domestic finance."
                    data-content-type="video">
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>
            </figcaption>
</figure>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The Obama administration is not backing down on its push to nominate a senior Wall Street banker to a major post at the Treasury Department. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Speaking at the DealBook Conference in Manhattan on Thursday, Treasury Secretary Jacob J. Lew said there were no discussions about withdrawing the nomination of Antonio Weiss, a Lazard investment banker, to become under secretary for domestic finance, despite growing opposition to his appointment. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&#8220;Antonio is extraordinarily well qualified,&#8221; Mr. Lew said. &#8220;We&#8217;re going to continue to press his nomination forward,&#8221; adding that there were &#8220;no conversations to pull back any nomination.&#8221;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Mr. Weiss, who has worked on international mergers and acquisitions and is a major bundler of campaign contributions for President Obama, has come under fire from Senator Elizabeth Warren, Democrat of Massachusetts, and Sheila C. Baer, a former chairwoman of the Federal Deposit Insurance Corporation, among others. They worry that his ties to Wall Street would lead to Treasury polices that go easy on banks. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">But Mr. Lew rebutted this line of attack. &#8220;You need multiple perspectives represented in a department like the Treasury Department,&#8221; he said. &#8220;You need people with a background where they&#8217;ve worked on things that they&#8217;re going to be making policy decisions on.&#8221;  </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Mr. Weiss&#8217;s nomination has also been criticized because he would be eligible for a roughly $20 million payout from Lazard should he accept the Treasury post. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&#8220;I understand the sticker shock,&#8221; Mr. Lew said. &#8220;I&#8217;m a little bit uncomfortable personally because my own compensation was never in the stratosphere. But the reality is we need people with certain levels of knowledge in positions of authority in our government.&#8221; </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Another critique of Mr. Weiss is that he worked on Burger King&#8217;s deal to acquire Tim Hortons, which will result in the American fast-food chain reincorporating in Canada in a so-called inversion deal. </p>
<div class="w480"><figure class="promo media video blog-video "
    data-videoid="100000003298642" data-media-action="modal" data-autoplay="" data-embedded="true" aria-label="media" role="group">
        <span class="visually-hidden">Video</span>

    <figcaption class="caption">
        <h4 class="headline">Treasury Secretary on Tax Inversions</h4>
		        <div class="caption-video">
                <div class="summary-credit">
            <p class="summary">Jacob J. Lew, the secretary of the Treasury, discussed tax inversions, saying, âitâs a bad thing when companies just change their address and get lower tax rates.â</p>
            <span class="credit video-credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder">
                                                                    <span class="visually-hidden">Publish Date </span>December 11, 2014.
                            </span>
            <span class="credit photo-credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder">
                                    Photo by Andrew Renneisen for The New York Times.
                                </span>
        </div>

                    <div class="sharetools-video-container">
                <div id="sharetools-video-tools-100000003298642"
                    class="sharetools sharetools-video-tools">
                    <ul>
                        <li class="sharetool embed-sharetool">
                            <a href="javascript:;" data-share="embed" data-modal-title="">
                                <i class="icon sprite-icon"></i>
                                <span class="sharetool-text ">embed</span>
                            </a>
                        </li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
                <div id="sharetools-video-inline-100000003298642"
                    class="sharetools sharetools-video-inline"
                    data-shares="facebook|,twitter|"
                    data-url="https://www.nytimes.com/video/business/100000003298642/treasury-secretary-on-tax-inversions.html?action=click&amp;contentCollection=business&amp;module=blog-video&amp;region=caption&amp;pgtype=article"
                    data-title="Treasury Secretary on Tax Inversions"
                    data-description="Jacob J. Lew, the secretary of the Treasury, discussed tax inversions, saying, âitâs a bad thing when companies just change their address and get lower tax rates.â"
                    data-content-type="video">
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>
            </figcaption>
</figure>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Mr. Lew led the crackdown on inversions this year, issuing a surprise notice in September that effectively put an end to most of the big deals, in which American corporations were buying smaller overseas competitors and moving abroad to lower their tax rates. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&#8220;The action that we took to shut down many of the inversions has slowed down the process,&#8221; Mr. Lew said. But, he added, &#8220;the root problem is that we need tax reform.&#8221;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Mr. Lew added that he was not opposed to international mergers, in principle. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&#8220;We think there&#8217;s a big difference between international mergers that are organic business mergers and deals that are based on taking tax advantages and, in the worse cases, just changing your address,&#8221; he said. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Mr. Lew said be believed business tax reform was possible in the next two years, and that Republicans and Democrats agreed on many of the main points, including lowering the statutory tax rate for companies.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&#8220;There&#8217;s growing consensus on business tax reform,&#8221; he said. &#8220;We need a statutory tax rate that is not the highest in the developed world.&#8221;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">In a wide-ranging interview with DealBook&#8217;s editor at large, Andrew Ross Sorkin, Mr. Lew also discussed energy policy and the effect of sanctions on Russia. </p>
<div class="w480"><figure class="promo media video blog-video "
    data-videoid="100000003298636" data-media-action="modal" data-autoplay="" data-embedded="true" aria-label="media" role="group">
        <span class="visually-hidden">Video</span>

    <figcaption class="caption">
        <h4 class="headline">Treasury Secretary on Russian Economy</h4>
		        <div class="caption-video">
                <div class="summary-credit">
            <p class="summary">Jacob J. Lew discussed the impact of oil prices and sanctions on Russia, saying thereâs a âperfect stormâ of pressures on the countryâs economy.</p>
            <span class="credit video-credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder">
                                                                    <span class="visually-hidden">Publish Date </span>December 11, 2014.
                            </span>
            <span class="credit photo-credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder">
                                    Photo by Andrew Renneisen for The New York Times.
                                </span>
        </div>

                    <div class="sharetools-video-container">
                <div id="sharetools-video-tools-100000003298636"
                    class="sharetools sharetools-video-tools">
                    <ul>
                        <li class="sharetool embed-sharetool">
                            <a href="javascript:;" data-share="embed" data-modal-title="">
                                <i class="icon sprite-icon"></i>
                                <span class="sharetool-text ">embed</span>
                            </a>
                        </li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
                <div id="sharetools-video-inline-100000003298636"
                    class="sharetools sharetools-video-inline"
                    data-shares="facebook|,twitter|"
                    data-url="https://www.nytimes.com/video/business/100000003298636/treasury-secretary-on-russian-economy.html?action=click&amp;contentCollection=business&amp;module=blog-video&amp;region=caption&amp;pgtype=article"
                    data-title="Treasury Secretary on Russian Economy"
                    data-description="Jacob J. Lew discussed the impact of oil prices and sanctions on Russia, saying thereâs a âperfect stormâ of pressures on the countryâs economy."
                    data-content-type="video">
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>
            </figcaption>
</figure>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Falling oil prices are largely a good thing for the economy, Mr. Lew said. &#8220;Lower energy prices are going to be a boost for consumer activity and confidence,&#8221; he said. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">And even though the lower prices are dragging down the stock prices of some American energy companies, Mr. Lew said, &#8220;It is a great success story that we are now producing oil in the quantities we are.&#8221;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">But falling oil prices are increasing pressure on Russia, he said. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&#8220;You&#8217;ve got a double whammy on the Russian economy right now,&#8221; Mr. Lew said. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">On the one hand, sanctions in response to the conflict in Ukraine were reducing capital flows into Russia, and more recently, lower oil prices were decreasing the profitability of one of Russia&#8217;s main exports. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&#8220;The pressure on Russia&#8217;s economy is quite substantial,&#8221; Mr. Lew said. &#8220;We&#8217;re seeing that daily in the movement of the ruble,&#8221; he continued, adding, &#8220;I hope what this leads to is a changing of Russia&#8217;s position on Ukraine.&#8221;</p>
	</div>
